{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060205A/1937111201/0572.xml":{"full_text":"STILL UNCERTAIN\nHouse May Have to Mark\nTime Until Farm Bill\nIs Completed.\nBy J. A. O\u2019LEARY.\nUncertainty surrounds the imme\ndiate program of Congress for the\nfirst week of the special session start\ning Monday, with the farm bill still\nIn the making In committee.\nAlthough House Democratic Leader\nBankhead and Senate Majority Leader\nBarkley will unite in an effort to get\nthrough as much as possible of the\nPresident\u2019s proposed legislation during\nthe special session, all indications are\nmuch of the program will drag over\ninto the regular January session.\nMr. Bankhead indicated yesterday\nthe House probably will have to mark\ntime for a few days until the farm\nmeasure is ready, and Mr. Barkley\narrived in the city with the statement\nhe would have to confer with com\nmittee chairmen before considering\nwhat the Senate should try to work on\nif the agricultural control bill is not\nready next week.\nOne thing is definite. The Presi\ndent will send his opening message to\nthe Capitol instead of delivering il\nin person. Senator Barkley is sched\nuled to see the Presid&it today.\nDecline Held Temporary.\nThe Senate majority leader expressed\nbelief the recent decline in business\nconditions is temporary and, in re\nsponse to questions, indicated he does\nnot believe the administration's pro\ngram for the approaching session will\naggravate that situation.\nGovernment reorganization, having\neconomy as one of its objectives,\nshould help rather than hurt the\nbusiness outlook, he observed. With\nregard to wage and hour legislation j\nhe said:\n\u2022\u2022Tf flint AAino t ei aa<iaa I\ndepression it would have caused it\nwhile under consideration in the\nSenate and before House committees,\nand not three months after Congress\nhad adjourned.\n\u201cWhatever depression may have oc\ncurred through fear of conditions of\ninternational unrest is temporary.\u201d\nThe Kentuckian, who is a member\nof the Finance Committee as well as\nfloor leader, was not ready to say\nwhat his position would be on re\nvision of the undistributed profits tax,\nfor which a move is steadily gaining\nmomentum as members of Congress\nreturn to the Capitol.\n\u201cX voted for the tax but did not\nforeclose myself from considering\namendments that may be suggested\nby experience,\u201d he said, indicating\nhe wants to study its operation more\ncarefully.\nIf the Senate has to wait for the\nHouse or its own committee to work\nout the farm bill, efforts probably\nwill be made by individual Senators\nto have that branch proceed first\nwith the anti-lynching bill or Gov\nernment reorganization, both of\nt* w hich are out of committee and ready l\non the calendar.\nGetting Set for the Special Session\nSenator Barkley, Demo<\ncratic leader of the Senate, as\nhe outlined program for the\nspecial session of Congress.\nSpeaker Bankhead of the House, who returned to Washing\nton yesterday for the special session, shoivn as he entered the\nWhite House for a luncheon engagement with President Roose\nvelt. \u2014A. P. and Wide World Photos.\n_ I _\nMURRAY FUNERAL\nWidely-Known Newspaper\nCorrespondent Dies at His\nApartment Here.\nFuneral services for Kenton Foster\nMurray, 61, widely-known newspaper\ncorrespondent, who was found dead\nfrom gas yesterday in his apartment\nat 1840 Blltmore street N.W., will be\nheld tomorrow at 11 a.m. at St. Mar\ngaret\u2019s Episcopal Church. Burial will\nbe in Rock Creek Cemetery.\nCoroner A. Magruder MacDonald,\nwho Issued a certificate of suicide in\nthe case, said a son, Francis E. Murray,\nsaid his father had been despondent\nover ill health.\nMr. Murray was Washington cor\nrespondent of the Norfolk, Va., Vir\nginian Pilot for many years. He also\nhad been correspondent for the Savan\nnah Morning News, the Detroit Free\nPress and the Charleston, C., News\nand Courier.\nMr. Murray was the brother-in-law\nof the late Joyce Kilmer, who wrote\nthe famous poem \u201cTrees.\"\nBesides his son, Mr. Murray is sur\nvived by his widow, Mrs. Lillian Mur\nray; a brother, Douglass Murray of\nFairfax, Va., and three sisters, Mrs.\nJoyce Kilmer of New Jersey, Mrs.\nStanley Greene of New York and Mrs.\nA. M. Clarke of Ohio.\nBesides his widow and son, Mr.\nMurray is survived by a brother,\nDouglass Murray of Fairfax, Va., and\nthree sisters, Mrs. Joyce Kilmer of\nNew Jersey; Mrs. Stanley Greene of\nNew York and Mrs. A. M. Clarke of\nOhio.\nFor admiring dates\nWear gloves by,^f \"a/es\nThey're smart, they\u2019re good and\nthey'll give the finishing touch to A\nthe well-groomed man whether (1)\nhe\u2019s obout town, about his\nbusiness or just being admired.\n\\fes G/oves\nin Swagger Sizes\n\nH s getting so it\u2019s almost a sign of o good\nmen\u2019s shop, to feature these gloves that\nore mode by descendants of \"The Glovers\nof Perth oldest gild\" of glove makers\nof record. Founded A. D 1165\nAtk for thorn by name,\ni\na man's ptove\nCopyright 1937, Gqf.Milli, Inc, Johmtpwn, R V.\n1 A\nonct arete rna/cKp if tite pteafe&t B\n5*ui\u00a3 THontf Ut ou/t Sretcte /fo&rtp B\nA AAA Superlatively Smart\n40UU fall suits j\nIn 5 Great Reduction Groups 1\nft\u2014\u2014\u25a0\u25a0!'y^7^T7TTT7rrmTrmrnr^,mm,,,, ss -1- g n n\nGROUP 4 GROUP 5 .7*^\n350 Scintillating COQ EA 250 Beautiful A ^0 T-' j\nStrand Fall Suit. VOBaUU Beau Geste Suiu W.UW pH\nAt a Saving of $6.50 to $10.50 to YOU\nUse YOUR Good Budget Account\u2014or Open One\nBp.\nI Please open a Kaufman Budget-Charge Account in my 1 2\nJ name. I understand NO CASH PAYMENT is needed t\nand that I may pay for my purchases in either semi- I M\u00a7p\nJ monthly or weekly payments in December, January and <4 Jr\nI February. J Jljgp\nName in Full___\u2022_\nI 1 ^Bpiil\nj Address-Home Phone_\nI Employed by__ J\nPosition-Monthly Income_\n8-11-12 1\nClip and Mail This Coupon to Me\u2014 ^^Bk^E J\u2018*\nat 1005 Pa. Ave. N.W. ty\nM\n\nft\n1\nBELL n